The Pseudo-Acron quotes from a lost work of Sallust, to the effect that Sertorius, after his defeat, thought of sailing into the Atlantic in search of the fabled islands of the blest, ‘ad insulas Fortunatas voluisse ire.' The genuineness of the quotation is confirmed by Servius, who, on Virg. Aen. 5. 735, refers to Sallust as having spoken os the μακάρων νῆσοι. Plutarch tells the same story in the life of Sertorius, ch. 9. It is very possible that Horace may have heard it, and that it may have suggested the conclusion of the Epode. Δ
